7. How do you manage permissions in PowerApps?

In Power Apps, permissions are usually managed in two ways:
â€” One is at the data source level (SharePoint or Dataverse), 
â€” Another one is Azure AD groups.

In the App OnStart property, 
I write a variable to check whether the logged-in user belongs to a specific Azure AD group by using the Office365Groups connector. 
First, I connect the Office365Groups connector to the app. 
Then, I create a global variable using the Set() function and check the group membership using the group ID. 
For example, I write:

Set(varIsManager, Office365Groups.IsMemberOfGroup("GroupID", User().Email).value)

This variable stores true or false based on whether the user is a member of that Azure AD group. 
Then throughout the app, I use this variable to control permissions, such as showing or hiding buttons, enabling edit access, or restricting certain features. 
This approach helps implement role-based access control dynamically when the app starts."


In SharePoint, 
I handle permissions by using SharePoint groups and permission levels to control access to lists and libraries.
First, I create groups like Owners, Members, and Visitors, or custom groups such as Managers and Employees based on business requirements. 
Then I assign permission levels like Read for view-only access, Contribute for adding and editing records, and Full Control for complete access. 
This ensures users only have the permissions required for their role.

In Dataverse, 
I manage security using security roles, which control what users can access and what actions they can perform on specific tables. 
First, I create or modify a security role in the Power Platform Admin Center and define permissions 
like Create, Read, Write, Delete, Append, and Append To for the required tables.
For example, 
in my project, I created separate roles like Requestor, Manager, and Admin. 
Requestors had only Create and Read access to their records, while Managers had Read and Write access, and Admins had full control.

After creating the security role, I assign it to users either directly or through Dataverse teams,
This way, whenever a user is added to that group, they automatically get the assigned permissions.















